item.title: A Pelo
item.dc:creator: pornceptual
item.description: A Pelo by Fernando Troya – a meeting between movement and image For A Pelo, the prequel to We play so hard it hurts presented […]
item.content:encoded:
A Pelo by Fernando Troya – a meeting between movement and image

For A Pelo, the prequel to We play so hard it hurts presented at the Amsterdam Fringe Festival, Fernando Troya dives into a darker period of his life: a time of hypersexualisation where queer desire becomes conflict, and the body its battlefield. A raw, physical duet where two bodies chase, trap, and release each other – until nothing is left but skin, breath, and exhaustion.
My work, which questions forms of intimacy often censored or marginalised, found an immediate resonance in A Pelo. I aim to move beyond the labels of “pornography” or “eroticism,” giving the image back its full complexity and leaving each viewer the freedom to project their own reading. This collaboration is not here to please. It’s here to own – to push the viewer to the point where the line between art and sex blurs, and the image becomes as physical as the dance itself.

Presented at the Amsterdam Fringe Festival 2025.
Amsterdam Fringe Festival , 5-6-7-8 Septembre 2025 at De Sloot.
Maker: Fernando Troya (Web / IG)
Models & Performance: Fernando Troya & Hugo Cabral Mendes
Assistant: Quentin Roger (Vimeo)
Music by Marko Ivic
Light design and scenigraphy Fernando Troya, Dana Claasen & Cerian Mason
Photographer: Ferran Sanchez Castillo
Business coach Martijn Schipper
Marketing Joren Lefebvre

item.title: If you know, you know
item.dc:creator: pornceptual
item.description: In queer communities, desire is spoken in codes — through gestures, fashion, glances, and symbols that carry history, intimacy, and play. With analogue photography as […]
item.content:encoded:
In queer communities, desire is spoken in codes — through gestures, fashion, glances, and symbols that carry history, intimacy, and play. With analogue photography as both a political and poetic choice, Versteeg’s work explores how identity, power, and longing intertwine in unspoken languages of connection and survival.

Photography and Concept: Studio Rik Versteeg
Models: David, Verdigris, Vincenzo, Eren, Tijn, Hassan, Celeste, Tracy , Rigonny, Special K, Rik Versteeg
Photography Assistant: Eren Kalpoe
Special Thanks: Maurice, Elvira, AC
This project is subsidised by CBK Rotterdam

item.title: Portals pt.3
item.dc:creator: pornceptual
item.description: Eva Allein is a Berlin-based photographer who began her artistic journey in an unexpected, unwanted setting: the club toilets of the city’s vibrant nightlife scene. […]
item.content:encoded:
Eva Allein is a Berlin-based photographer who began her artistic journey in an unexpected, unwanted setting: the club toilets of the city’s vibrant nightlife scene. Initially taking photos out of boredom with her phone instead of taking unnecessary lines, she soon discovered a rich tapestry of human emotion and transformation within these confined spaces. Her work captures the microcosm of Berlin club toilets, documenting everything that happens inside a club’s stall.

Eva views club toilets as metaphysical portals: “Club Toilets are Portals: you are not the same person when you come out of it; your mind is in a different metaphysical state as well as your body. Perceptions are enhanced, accelerated or slowed down, magic and mistakes are at hand. Shall we learn from whatever we put up our noses or shall we just be passive and let it take control? Is it just for recreation or is it our fleeting tiny DIY quantum leap? Whatever our intention is, club toilets are always, unapologetically, full.”

BY EVA ALLEIN
